e\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 19 Nov 2018 17:00:40 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"ip address filter\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:24:\"google analytics filters\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"stop tracking\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:50:\"exclude WordPress admin from Google Analytics data\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=104698\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:674:\"<p>Do you want to stop Google Analytics from tracking logged in users? By default, Google Analytics tracks each and every pageview on your site including admin pageviews and visits by bots. When youâ€™re writing, editing, and previewing on your site, it records each of your visit as a real pageview and prepares reports including those [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-stop-google-analytics-from-tracking-logged-in-users-in-wordpress/\">How to Stop Google Analytics from Tracking Logged In Users in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Shahzad Saeed\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8106:\"<p>Do you want to stop Google Analytics from tracking logged in users? By default, Google Analytics tracks each and every pageview on your site including admin pageviews and visits by bots. When youâ€™re writing, editing, and previewing on your site, it records each of your visit as a real pageview and prepares reports including those logged in pageviews. </p>\n<p>The downside of such reports is that they prevent you from seeing your real website metrics. In this article, weâ€™ll show you how to exclude WordPress admin (logged in users) from Google Analytics tracking. </p>\n<h3>Why Exclude Logged in WordPress Users from Google Analytics</h3>\n<p>Google Analytics is the most popular web analytics tool that helps you to track how your site visitors are interacting with your site. It provides you with detailed reports on your site traffic and their behavior on your site. Using your Analytics data, you can make informed marketing decisions and grow your business. </p>\n<p>However, your analytics data can be misleading if theyâ€™re not exact. </p>\n<p>Thereâ€™re many reasons why Google Analytics data can be inaccurate. One of the most common reasons is tracking logged in users. When youâ€™re logged in as administrator, author, editor, or any user role and previewing your site, Google Analytics counts your visits as real visits and adds to your siteâ€™s total visits. </p>\n<p>As a result, you may see a spike in your pageviews but that isn&#8217;t due to traffic increase in real. That&#8217;s because Google Analytics is tracking your admin visits as real visitors. </p>\n<p>For example, if you&#8217;re frequently working and editing on your site, you can see a huge increase in traffic. Similarly, you may see a remarkable traffic increase on a page/ post after some modification on it. </p>\n<p>Such distorted data cannot help you to improve your marketing. So, it is always better to ensure that your own visits are not tracked by Google Analytics.</p>\n<h3>How to Exclude WordPress Admin from Google Analytics Data</h3>\n<p>There are many ways to stop tracking WordPress admin visits in Google Analytics. For example, IP address filtering. Creating an IP address filter whitelists your IP address and stops tracking visits originating from that specific IP. This way, it doesnâ€™t discern the actual traffic with your own traffic.</p>\n<p>However, the downside is it is only applicable if youâ€™re using a static IP address, that doesnâ€™t change.</p>\n<p>A much better solution is to disable the logged in visitors tracking, so you can stop tracking your own visits on your <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/guides/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"How to Make a WordPress Website â€“ Step by Step Guide (Free)\">WordPress website</a> even if youâ€™re using a dynamic IP. </p>\n<p>Fortunately, there&#8217;s a very simple solution! <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a> plugin makes it really easy to exclude WordPress admin traffic from Google Analytics. </p>\n<p>Before we get started, weâ€™re assuming that youâ€™re using <a href=\"http://monsterinsights.com/pricing/\">MonsterInsights </a>on your site and <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-properly-setup-google-analytics-in-wordpress/\">configured it with Google Analytics</a>.</p>\n<p>Navigate to <strong>Insights &raquo; Settings</strong> from your WordPress dashboard. Then click on the <strong>Tracking</strong> tab at the top. Youâ€™ll now see the <strong>Engagement</strong> page.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-104701\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/ignore-user-roles-from-tracking.jpg\" alt=\"ignore user roles from tracking\" width=\"560\" height=\"292\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/ignore-user-roles-from-tracking.jpg 560w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/ignore-user-roles-from-tracking-300x156.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px\" /></p>\n<p>You can now specify user roles to exclude from tracking in Google Analytics.</p>\n<p>After specifying user roles youâ€™d like to exclude, click <strong>Save Changes</strong>.</p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s it!</p>\n<p>Youâ€™ve successfully stopped tracking visits from the specified user roles in Google Analytics.</p>\n<h3>Creating a Google Analytics Filter to Exclude WordPress Admin Traffic (Alternative Way)</h3>\n<p>With <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a>, it&#8217;s really easy and quick to exclude WordPress admin traffic from Google Analytics reports. But if you insist on <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-google-analytics-to-wordpress-without-a-plugin/\">using Google Analytics without a plugin</a>, you&#8217;ll need to create a Google Analytics filter to exclude WordPress traffic. Here&#8217;s how to do that step-by-step.</p>\n<p>First of all, you&#8217;ll need to login to your Google Analytics account by visiting the official website. Then, go to <strong>Admin</strong> option at the bottom of the left panel. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin.jpg\" alt=\"ga-admin\" width=\"250\" height=\"586\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169257\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin.jpg 250w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin-128x300.jpg 128w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 250px) 100vw, 250px\" /></p>\n<p>After that, click <strong>Filters</strong> option below <strong>View</strong> column. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/ga-filters.jpg\" alt=\"ga-filters\" width=\"620\" height=\"531\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-170508\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/ga-filters.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/ga-filters-300x257.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, click the <strong>Add Filter Button</strong>. Next, you&#8217;ll see a page to add a filter to exclude WordPress admin page traffic. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/add-filter-exclude-admin-from-ga.jpg\" alt=\"add-filter-exclude-admin-from-ga\" width=\"471\" height=\"400\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-170509\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/add-filter-exclude-admin-from-ga.jpg 471w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/add-filter-exclude-admin-from-ga-300x255.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 471px) 100vw, 471px\" /></p>\n<p>First, you&#8217;ll need to enter a filter name. Then, select <strong>Custom</strong> from the Filter Type options. Then, you&#8217;ll see <strong>Exclude</strong> option at first. </p>\n<p>Choose <strong>Request URI</strong> from Filter Field options and enter <strong>wp-login.php</strong> in the Filter Pattern field. </p>\n<p>Then go ahead and click <strong>Save</strong> button. </p>\n<p>Now Google Analytics will exclude traffic from your WordPress admin page (wp-login.php). </p>\n<p>We hope this article helped you to learn how to stop Google Analytics from tracking logged in users and get accurate reports. </p>\n<p>If youâ€™re also running an email marketing campaign on your site, you might want to <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-find-your-most-profitable-email-campaigns-in-google-analytics/\">find out the most profitable email campaigns in Google Analytics</a>. And donâ€™t forget to follow us on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/monsterinsights\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blanks\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/monsterinsights\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blanks\">Facebook</a> for more Google Analytics tutorials.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-stop-google-analytics-from-tracking-logged-in-users-in-wordpress/\">How to Stop Google Analytics from Tracking Logged In Users in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:109:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-stop-google-analytics-from-tracking-logged-in-users-in-wordpress/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"4\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:64:\"How to Track Links and Button Clicks in WordPress (Step by Step)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:201:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-track-links-and-button-clicks-in-wordpress-step-by-step/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=how-to-track-links-and-button-clicks-in-wordpress-step-by-step\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:103:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-track-links-and-button-clicks-in-wordpress-step-by-step/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 15 Nov 2018 14:25:59 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"event tracking\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:23:\"file downloads tracking\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"forms tracking\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:23:\"affiliate link tracking\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:23:\"outbound links tracking\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=155546\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:673:\"<p>Do you want to track links and button clicks in WordPress? You can use Google Analytics; however, you&#8217;d have to manually add in a bunch of events tracking code because GA doesn&#8217;t track links and button clicks by default.Â  Or, you can use the smartest Google Analytics WordPress plugin on the market,Â MonsterInsights, to easily automate [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-track-links-and-button-clicks-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\">How to Track Links and Button Clicks in WordPress (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Sunita Rai\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20352:\"<p>Do you want to track links and button clicks in WordPress? You can use Google Analytics; however, you&#8217;d have to manually add in a bunch of events tracking code because GA doesn&#8217;t track links and button clicks by default.Â  Or, you can use the smartest Google Analytics WordPress plugin on the market,Â <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a>, to easily automate your links and button clicks tracking.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâ€™ll show you how to track links and button clicks in WordPress step-by-step using MonsterInsights.</p>\n<h3>Why Track Links and Button Clicks in WordPress?</h3>\n<p>Links and buttons are major points of user interaction on your site. Most often, youâ€™ll use links and buttons as the call-to-action elements that you want your users to click.</p>\n<p>Letâ€™s see a few examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Affiliate links</strong> will lead your users to buy your referred products and let you earn some referral income.</li>\n<li><strong>Add to Cart</strong> <strong>buttons</strong> will lead your customers to buy a product from your store.</li>\n<li><strong>Form Submit</strong> <strong>buttons</strong> will help your users to send a message using your online contact form.</li>\n<li><strong>File download</strong> <strong>buttons</strong> will help your users to download files from your site.</li>\n<li><strong>Outbound links</strong> will redirect your readers to other websites (resources) you want them to go to.</li>\n<li><strong>Call-to-action</strong> <strong>buttons</strong> will take your users to your product landing pages, and other important conversion pages.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>As you place these links and buttons for users to engage with on your site, tracking them can help you understand how exactly your users are interacting with them.</p>\n<p>By tracking your links and button clicks, you can find out which type of links are getting the most clicks, which buttons are the most popular, and much more. Then, you can analyze the reports and make improvements.</p>\n<p>After you&#8217;ve optimized your links and buttons, theyâ€™re sure to get more visibility and more clicks. The more clicks, the more the interaction and engagement. When users are more engaged on your site, your site conversions will increase significantly.</p>\n<p>In a nutshell, tracking events like links and button clicks can help you to understand exactly how your users interact on your site so that you can make informed strategies for your business growth.</p>\n<h3>Using MonsterInsights to Track Links and Button Clicks</h3>\n<p>Google Analytics can provide you with your entire website&#8217;s metrics but it tracks only pageviews by default. If you want to track events such as links and button clicks,Â  or transactions like eCommerce purchases, youâ€™ll need to manually set up tracking for each event or transaction.</p>\n<p>Unfortunately, setting up event tracking in Google Analytics is somewhat tricky, so newbies can get lost quickly. If you lack experience, youâ€™ll need to hire an expert to help you set up your Google Analytics tracking.</p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s why we recommend you use <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a> to track your Google Analytics metrics with ease.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-151922\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/monsterinsights-wp-google-analytics-plugin.jpg\" alt=\"monsterinsights-wp-google-analytics-plugin\" width=\"560\" height=\"261\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/monsterinsights-wp-google-analytics-plugin.jpg 560w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/monsterinsights-wp-google-analytics-plugin-300x140.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px\" /></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a> makes the entire process of using Google Analytics in WordPress super simple so anyone can easily set up Google Analytics and configure advanced trackings such as events and transactions.</p>\n<p>To get started, youâ€™ll need to <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/pricing/\">download MonsterInsights</a>, install it on WordPress, and then connect your site with your Google Analytics account. You can set up Google Analytics in WordPress with just a few clicks using MonsterInsights.</p>\n<p>For detailed instructions, hereâ€™s our guide on <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-properly-setup-google-analytics-in-wordpress/\">how to properly set up Google Analytics in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Once itâ€™s set up, you can view the overview report for your site on your WordPress dashboard from the <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/introducing-google-analytics-dashboard-widget-for-monsterinsights/\">MonsterInsights Dashboard Widget</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-154759\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/monsterinsightsdashboardwidget.png\" alt=\"Google Analytics Dashboard Widget for WordPress by MonsterInsights\" width=\"620\" height=\"420\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/monsterinsightsdashboardwidget.png 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/monsterinsightsdashboardwidget-300x203.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>To view detailed reports for your site, youâ€™ll need to go to <strong>Insights Â» Reports</strong> from your WordPress dashboard.</p>\n<p>Now, letâ€™s go ahead and check how to track links and button clicks in WordPress using MonsterInsights.</p>\n<h3>1. Tracking Affiliate Links in WordPress</h3>\n<p>MonsterInsights makes affiliate links tracking really simple. Itâ€™ll take just a few clicks to complete the setup process.</p>\n<p>Navigate to <strong>Insights Â» Settings</strong> from your WordPress dashboard and then click on the <strong>Tracking</strong> tab at the top of the page. Then, go to the <strong>Affiliate Links</strong> tab in the left taskbar.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-108939\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/affiliate-link-tracking.jpg\" alt=\"affiliate link tracking in wordpress\" width=\"560\" height=\"578\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/affiliate-link-tracking.jpg 560w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/affiliate-link-tracking-291x300.jpg 291w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px\" /></p>\n<p>There, youâ€™ll see 2 fields:</p>\n<p><strong>i) Set path for internal links to track as outbound links:</strong></p>\n<p>If youâ€™re using an affiliate management plugin like <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/refer/thirstyaffiliates/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">ThirstyAffiliates</a>, your affiliate links will look like:</p>\n<p>http://example.com/recommends/your-affiliate-link</p>\n<p>In the above example, your affiliate link begins with /recommends/.</p>\n<p>You can simply copy the prefix <strong>/recommends/</strong> on this field, so Google Analytics can identify which internal links are affiliate links. If you use multiple prefixes, you can separate them with a comma: /recommends/,/out/.</p>\n<p><strong>ii) Label for those links:</strong></p>\n<p>The label in your Google Analytics report lets you identify where the click came from. For example, you can add a label <strong>aff</strong> to your affiliate links.</p>\n<p>After you complete these 2 fields, click <strong>Save Changes</strong>.</p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s it. Youâ€™re done with affiliate links tracking setup.</p>\n<p>Now, you can view the reports by visiting <strong> Insights Â» Reports Â» Publishers</strong> from your WordPress dashboard.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-155898\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/affiliate-link-tracking-report-monsterinsights.jpg\" alt=\"affiliate-link-tracking-report-monsterinsights\" width=\"560\" height=\"600\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/affiliate-link-tracking-report-monsterinsights.jpg 560w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/affiliate-link-tracking-report-monsterinsights-280x300.jpg 280w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px\" /></p>\n<p>You can always click the <strong>View All Affiliate Links Report</strong> to view more reports in Google Analytics.</p>\n<p>If you want detailed instructions, hereâ€™s our complete guide on <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-set-up-affiliate-link-tracking-in-wordpress/\">setting up affiliate links tracking</a>.</p>\n<h3>2. eCommerce Tracking in WordPress</h3>\n<p>MonsterInsights eCommerce tracking helps you to track all the data you need for your WooCommerce or Easy Digital Downloads store. The eCommerce report will show total <strong>Add to Cart</strong> button clicks, total <strong>Remove from the Cart</strong> button clicks, and total <strong>Buy</strong> button clicks for your online store.</p>\n<p>To get started, youâ€™ll need to enable eCommerce tracking in Google Analytics first. If you donâ€™t know how to do that, hereâ€™s our <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/docs/enable-ecommerce-tracking/\">step-by-step guide to enable eCommerce tracking</a>.</p>\n<p>After that, you&#8217;ll need to install <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/addon/ecommerce/\">MonsterInsights eCommerce Addon</a>Â on your WordPress site. Then, navigate to <strong>Insights Â» Settings</strong> and click on the <strong>Tracking</strong> tab on the top.</p>\n<p>Then, in the left taskbar, navigate to the <strong>eCommerce</strong> tab and select the checkbox near <strong>Use Enhanced eCommerce</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-155900\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/enable-enhanced-ecommerce-monsterinsights.jpg\" alt=\"enable-enhanced-ecommerce-monsterinsights\" width=\"560\" height=\"385\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/enable-enhanced-ecommerce-monsterinsights.jpg 560w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/enable-enhanced-ecommerce-monsterinsights-300x206.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px\" /></p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s it! Now, you can view your eCommerce reports by going to <strong>Insights Â» Reports Â» eCommerce</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-143121\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/MonsterInsights-eCommerce-Report.png\" alt=\"MonsterInsights eCommerce Report\" width=\"560\" height=\"362\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/MonsterInsights-eCommerce-Report.png 560w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/MonsterInsights-eCommerce-Report-300x194.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px\" /></p>\n<p>As you scroll down, youâ€™ll see how many times the <strong>Add to Cart</strong> button was clicked and also the <strong>Remove from the Cart</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-148172\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/MonsterInsights-eCommerce-Report.2.png\" alt=\"MonsterInsights eCommerce Report.2\" width=\"560\" height=\"312\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/MonsterInsights-eCommerce-Report.2.png 560w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/MonsterInsights-eCommerce-Report.2-300x167.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px\" /></p>\n<h3>3. Form Submit Button Tracking in WordPress</h3>\n<p>MonsterInsights comes with a powerful <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/addon/forms/\">Forms Tracking addon</a> to automate forms conversion tracking.</p>\n<p>By enabling forms tracking, you can view which forms are triggering the most views and submissions. The number of total submissions for forms are counted when a user clicks the <strong>Submit</strong> or <strong>Send</strong> for a form.</p>\n<p>To enable forms tracking, youâ€™ll need to install and activate the Forms addon in your site. Navigate to <strong>Insights Â» Addons</strong> and find the <strong>Forms Addon</strong>. Then, click the <strong>Install</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-104951\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/forms-addon.jpg\" alt=\"forms addon\" width=\"381\" height=\"478\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/forms-addon.jpg 381w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/forms-addon-239x300.jpg 239w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 381px) 100vw, 381px\" /></p>\n<p>Youâ€™ll see the button changed into the <strong>Activate</strong> option. Simply click the button to activate the addon.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-104952\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/forms-addon-activate.jpg\" alt=\"forms addon activate\" width=\"382\" height=\"477\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/forms-addon-activate.jpg 382w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/forms-addon-activate-240x300.jpg 240w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 382px) 100vw, 382px\" /></p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s it. Youâ€™ve completed the setup process. Now you can view your form conversion reports by going to <strong>Insights Â» Reports Â» Forms</strong> from your WordPress dashboard.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-152780\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/wpforms-forms-reports.jpg\" alt=\"wpforms-forms-reports\" width=\"560\" height=\"543\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/wpforms-forms-reports.jpg 560w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/wpforms-forms-reports-300x291.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px\" /></p>\n<p>As you can see above in the screenshot, it&#8217;ll show you how many impressions and conversions each of your forms triggered. The number of conversions refer to the total clicks on <strong>Submit</strong> or <strong>Send</strong> button in your forms.</p>\n<h3>4. Tracking File Download Button Clicks in WordPress</h3>\n<p>If you&#8217;ve added downloadable resources on your WordPress site, tracking the downloads can help you discover your most popular resources and help to make better resources.</p>\n<p>MonsterInsights makes <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/feature/file-download-tracking/\">file downloads tracking</a> very easy for WordPress users. You can set up this feature in just a few clicks.</p>\n<p>First, you&#8217;ll need to go to <strong>Insights Â» Settings Â» Tracking</strong>. Next, click on <strong>File Downloads</strong> tab in the left menu.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-88528\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/download-tracking.jpg\" alt=\"download tracking\" width=\"540\" height=\"365\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/download-tracking.jpg 540w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/download-tracking-300x203.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 540px) 100vw, 540px\" /></p>\n<p>You can select <strong>Event</strong> to track your site downloads. Then, in the field below, you can see the file extensions that MonsterInsights tracks by default.</p>\n<p>To track downloads of more file extensions, you just need to add them to the field, separated by a comma.</p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s it! The plugin will now track all the clicks users will perform to download your resources.</p>\n<p>Now, you can see your download reports by going to <strong>Insights Â» Reports Â» Publishers</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-155903\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/file-downloads-report-monsterinsights.jpg\" alt=\"file-downloads-report-monsterinsights\" width=\"560\" height=\"375\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/file-downloads-report-monsterinsights.jpg 560w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/file-downloads-report-monsterinsights-300x201.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px\" /></p>\n<p>As you can see in the screenshot above, you can view the total clicks each of your downloadable resources has triggered.</p>\n<h3>5. Tracking Outbound Links in WordPress</h3>\n<p>MonsterInsights tracks your outbound links clicks automatically and shows you the reports in <strong>Publishers</strong>. But youâ€™ll need to purchase at least theÂ <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/pricing/\">Plus plan</a> to view the Publishers report.</p>\n<p>Once youâ€™ve set up MonsterInsights properly, you can go to <strong>Insights Â» Reports Â» Publishers</strong> from your WordPress dashboard to view your outbound links reports.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-155904\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/outbound-links-report-monsterinsights.jpg\" alt=\"outbound-links-report-monsterinsights\" width=\"560\" height=\"555\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/outbound-links-report-monsterinsights.jpg 560w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/outbound-links-report-monsterinsights-150x150.jpg 150w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/outbound-links-report-monsterinsights-300x297.jpg 300w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/outbound-links-report-monsterinsights-100x100.jpg 100w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px\" /></p>\n<p>As you can see in the screenshot above, you can view your top outbound links with total clicks in MonsterInsights&#8217; Publishers report.</p>\n<h3>6. Tracking Custom Links in WordPress</h3>\n<p>In addition to the automated options for tracking link and button clicks discussed above, MonsterInsights now lets you track your custom links such as call-to-action buttons, your site subdomains, and other important links easily.</p>\n<p>The latest <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/announcing-monsterinsights-7-3-page-insights-addon-real-time-reports-and-more/\">MosterInsights version 7.3</a> has introduced a new <strong>Custom Link Attribution</strong> feature to allow you easily add custom event tracking to your custom links. So, make sure that you&#8217;ve got the latest version of the plugin on your site.</p>\n<p>With this new Custom Link Attribution Feature, you can track your call-to-action (CTA) buttons and find out how important theyâ€™re for your site conversions. Similarly, you can add event tracking to other important links such as your subdomains and see how users interact with those links.</p>\n<p>Itâ€™s easy to add custom event tracking to your custom WordPress links with MonsterInsights. All you need to do is to add the following data-variable tags to the HTML of your link:</p>\n<p><strong>&lt;a href=&#8221;https://www.monsterinsights.com&#8221; data-vars-ga-category=&#8221;Custom Category&#8221; data-vars-ga-action=&#8221;Custom Action&#8221; data-vars-ga-label=&#8221;Custom Label&#8221;&gt;Example&lt;/a&gt;</strong></p>\n<p>Once you add the tags, MonsterInsights will track your WordPress links and provide you with detailed reports.</p>\n<p>The Custom Link Attribution feature also supports Google AMP pages, so you can precisely track your AMP optimized custom links.</p>\n<p>We hope this article helped you to learn how to track links and button clicks in WordPress using Google Analytics.</p>\n<p>You might also want to check out our guide on <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/4-ways-to-boost-your-seo-rankings-with-google-analytics/\">4 ways to boost your SEO rankings with Google Analytics</a>.</p>\n<p>Also, donâ€™t forget to follow us on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> for more Google Analytics tutorials.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-track-links-and-button-clicks-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\">How to Track Links and Button Clicks in WordPress (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:100:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-track-links-and-button-clicks-in-wordpress-step-by-step/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:63:\"How to Track Formidable Forms Conversions with Google Analytics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:203:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-track-formidable-forms-conversions-with-google-analytics/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=how-to-track-formidable-forms-conversions-with-google-analytics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:104:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-track-formidable-forms-conversions-with-google-analytics/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 12 Nov 2018 15:22:30 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"forms tracking\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"forms addon\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"optimize forms conversions\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=169682\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:676:\"<p>Want to track your Formidable Forms conversions to see which forms are most loved on your site? With Google Analytics, you can track your forms conversions, but itâ€™s got quite a learning curve for beginners. Fortunately, thereâ€™re smart tools like MonsterInsights to help you set up forms tracking and other advanced events trackings easily in [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-track-formidable-forms-conversions-with-google-analytics/\">How to Track Formidable Forms Conversions with Google Analytics</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Sunita Rai\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12778:\"<p>Want to track your Formidable Forms conversions to see which forms are most loved on your site? With Google Analytics, you can track your forms conversions, but itâ€™s got quite a learning curve for beginners. Fortunately, thereâ€™re smart tools like <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a> to help you set up forms tracking and other advanced events trackings easily in Google Analytics.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâ€™ll show you how to track your Formidable Forms conversions with Google Analytics the easy way: using MonsterInsights.</p>\n<h3>Setting Up Formidable Forms Tracking in Google Analytics</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/refer/formidable-pro/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Formidable Forms</a> is the most advanced WordPress form builder plugin available on the market. The plugin lets you create advanced forms like quizzes, surveys, payment forms, registration forms, directories, job board listings, etc. easily. Itâ€™s one of the <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/best-wordpress-contact-form-plugins/\">best form builder plugins for WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>You can set up Formidable Forms tracking with Google Analytics in 2 ways:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>By Setting Up Event Goals in Google Analytics â€“ The Manual Way</li>\n<li>By Using MonsterInsights â€“ The Automatic (Easy) Way</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you choose the first method, youâ€™ll need to <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-create-a-goal-in-google-analytics-to-track-conversions/\">set up event goals in Google Analytics&#8217;</a> interface and define your form conversions as event goals. This method is the far less user-friendly approach. If you arenâ€™t a developer, itâ€™ll take a lot of your time and effort to learn, or take a lot of your money to hire a developer.</p>\n<p>Whereas the second method is speedy and effortless. It takes just a few steps to set up forms tracking in Google Analytics using MonsterInsights. All you need to do to set up forms tracking is to install the <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/addon/forms/\">MonsterInsights Forms addon</a> in your WordPress dashboard. Then, MonsterInsights handles the rest automatically.</p>\n<h3>Benefits of Using MonsterInsights vs. Manual Setup to Track Forms</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-157422\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg\" alt=\"monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress\" width=\"620\" height=\"250\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress-300x121.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a> is the best Google Analytics plugin for WordPress. It simplifies the entire process of using Google Analytics on your WordPress site. It comes with a set of simple-yet-powerful <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/features/\">addons</a>, like the Forms addon, to allow you track advanced metrics easily.</p>\n<p>Thereâ€™re many benefits of using MonsterInsights&#8217; Forms addon versus setting up forms tracking manually in Google Analytics&#8217; interface. Below are just a few key benefits:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Easy and quick setup</strong>: You can set up forms tracking on your site easily, in just a few minutes. Youâ€™d need to spend a lot of time and energy or hire a developer to set up forms tracking otherwise.</li>\n<li><strong>Set up and view reports within your WordPress dashboard</strong>: You can set up forms tracking and view your forms reports within your WordPress dashboard. Hence, you can keep working on your site while viewing your Analytics reports &#8211; you donâ€™t need to navigate away from your site.</li>\n<li><strong>Most comprehensive reports</strong>: MonsterInsights provides you with most comprehensive reports for all your website metrics. Your forms conversion reports in MonsterInsights are way more simple and easy to understand than in the Google Analytics platform itself.</li>\n<li><strong>Works with your favorite form builder</strong>: Alongside Formidable Forms, MonsterInsights supports all the major WordPress form builder plugins including <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">WPForms</a> and <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/refer/ninja-forms/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Ninja Forms</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Clearly, using MonsterInsights Forms addon is the best option for tracking Formidable Forms conversions. You can buy <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/pricing/\">MonsterInsights Pro</a> to enjoy this feature.</p>\n<h3>How to Track Formidable Forms Conversions Using MonsterInsights</h3>\n<p>First, install the <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/pricing/\">MonsterInsights plugin</a> on your WordPress site and <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-properly-setup-google-analytics-in-wordpress/\">set up Google Analytics using the plugin</a>.</p>\n<p>After that, navigate to <strong>Insights Â» Addons</strong> from your WordPress dashboard and find <strong>Forms Addon</strong>. Then, click the <strong>Install</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-104951\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/forms-addon.jpg\" alt=\"install mi forms addon\" width=\"381\" height=\"478\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/forms-addon.jpg 381w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/forms-addon-239x300.jpg 239w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 381px) 100vw, 381px\" /></p>\n<p>You&#8217;ll see the button change to theÂ <strong>Activate</strong> option. Simply click the button to activate the addon.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-104952\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/forms-addon-activate.jpg\" alt=\"forms addon activate\" width=\"382\" height=\"477\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/forms-addon-activate.jpg 382w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/forms-addon-activate-240x300.jpg 240w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 382px) 100vw, 382px\" /></p>\n<p>After that, you&#8217;ll see the addon&#8217;s status asÂ <strong>active</strong>.</p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s it! You have completed the setup process in literally 2 clicks!</p>\n<p>You donâ€™t need any further configuration.</p>\n<p>Now, the plugin will automatically start tracking your Formidable Forms conversions. Normally, Google Analytics takes 24 to 48 hours to track events like form conversions, so you can check your reports after the given time.</p>\n<p>Now, letâ€™s go ahead and learn how to view your form conversion reports.</p>\n<h3>How to View Formidable Forms Conversion Reports</h3>\n<p>With <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights Forms</a>, you can view all your important website data right in your WordPress dashboard without having to open another website. Yes, thatâ€™s right! You can view your forms conversion reports inside your dashboard as well.</p>\n<p>To view your forms reports, go to <strong>Insights Â» Reports</strong> from your WordPress dashboard. There, you&#8217;ll see the <strong>Overview Report</strong> of your entire site.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-157435\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-overview-report.jpg\" alt=\"monsterinsights-overview-report\" width=\"620\" height=\"575\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-overview-report.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-overview-report-300x278.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>To view your form reports, click the <strong>Forms</strong> link.</p>\n<p>Then, you&#8217;ll see your Formidable Forms reports just like in the screenshot below.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169695\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/formidble-forms-reports-in-mi-dashboard-reports.jpg\" alt=\"formidble-forms-reports-in-mi-dashboard-reports\" width=\"620\" height=\"532\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/formidble-forms-reports-in-mi-dashboard-reports.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/formidble-forms-reports-in-mi-dashboard-reports-300x257.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>The first column from the left is the list of your Formidable formsâ€™ names. The second column is the number of impressions, and the third is the number of successful form submissions. The last column shows the conversion rate for your forms.</p>\n<p>Itâ€™s very simple and easy to understand!</p>\n<p>Now, if you want to view more details regarding your form conversions, you can click theÂ <strong>View Full Forms Report</strong> button at the bottom of the report.</p>\n<p>Doing so will redirect you to <strong>Google Analytics Â» Behavior Â» Events Â» Top Events</strong> in your Google Analytics account. If you arenâ€™t already logged in, youâ€™ll need to log into your Google Analytics account to view this report.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169696\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/formidable-forms-conversion-reports-ga.jpg\" alt=\"formidable-forms-conversion-reports-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"486\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/formidable-forms-conversion-reports-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/formidable-forms-conversion-reports-ga-300x235.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>As you can see above in the screenshot, it shows the total impressions and conversions triggered by all your forms.</p>\n<p>If you want to view the events for each form individually, click on <strong>Event Label</strong> link in your Forms report <strong>Primary Dimension</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169697\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/formidable-forms-individual-form-reports-ga.jpg\" alt=\"formidable-forms-individual-form-reports-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"570\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/formidable-forms-individual-form-reports-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/formidable-forms-individual-form-reports-ga-300x276.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now you&#8217;ll see the total events for each of your Formidable Forms forms individually. Total events include both impressions and conversions for your forms.</p>\n<p>If you want to see impressions and conversions separately for each form, click your form names one-by-one.</p>\n<p>After doing that, hereâ€™s how theÂ <strong>Impression</strong> and <strong>Conversion</strong> data are provided separately:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169698\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/view-formidable-forms-reports-for-each-form.jpg\" alt=\"view-formidable-forms-reports-for-each-form\" width=\"620\" height=\"477\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/view-formidable-forms-reports-for-each-form.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/view-formidable-forms-reports-for-each-form-300x231.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s all.</p>\n<p>We hope this article helped you learn how to track your Formidable Forms conversions with Google Analytics. If you found MonsterInsights useful, <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/pricing/\">download it today</a>!</p>\n<p>You may also want to see our detailed guide on how to <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-find-real-time-reports-in-google-analytics/\">find real-time reports in Google Analytics</a>.</p>\n<p>Also, donâ€™t forget to follow us on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> for more Google Analytics tutorials.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-track-formidable-forms-conversions-with-google-analytics/\">How to Track Formidable Forms Conversions with Google Analytics</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:101:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-track-formidable-forms-conversions-with-google-analytics/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:48:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:64:\"How to Add PayPal to Referral Exclusion List in Google Analytics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:205:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-paypal-to-referral-exclusion-list-in-google-analytics/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=how-to-add-paypal-to-referral-exclusion-list-in-google-analytics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:105:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-paypal-to-referral-exclusion-list-in-google-analytics/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 08 Nov 2018 16:03:33 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"Google Analytics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:23:\"referral exclusion list\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=169180\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:683:\"<p>Want to learn how to add PayPal to your referral exclusion list in Google Analytics? If youâ€™re using PayPal to accept payments, Google Analytics will list PayPal as the referrer source instead of original referrer sites. This prevents you from seeing the original referrer websites contributing to your conversions. To prevent tracking PayPal as referrer [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-paypal-to-referral-exclusion-list-in-google-analytics/\">How to Add PayPal to Referral Exclusion List in Google Analytics</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Sunita Rai\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7299:\"<p>Want to learn how to add PayPal to your referral exclusion list in Google Analytics? If youâ€™re using PayPal to accept payments, Google Analytics will list PayPal as the referrer source instead of original referrer sites. This prevents you from seeing the original referrer websites contributing to your conversions.</p>\n<p>To prevent tracking PayPal as referrer and to track the real referrers, you need to add PayPal to the referral exclusion list in Google Analytics. And, hereâ€™s how to do that in just a few steps.</p>\n<h3>Why Google Analytics Lists PayPal as the Referrer â€“ Explained</h3>\n<p>When using PayPal as your payment gateway, your customers leave your site and log into PayPal&#8217;s website to make a payment. After they pay successfully, they return to your site, often to a Thank You page, and the conversion is made.</p>\n<p>Essentially, Google Analytics tracks the last website visited before conversion as the referral source for that conversion. Hence, it attributes PayPal as the referral source for the transaction. But, in reality, the referral source is where the customer found your website or product link, not PayPal.</p>\n<p>For example, a customer comes to your site from an affiliate website and decides to buy a product. After adding the product to their cart, your site redirects the user to PayPal&#8217;s website to make the payment. Now, they log into PayPal, pay for the product, and return to your site. And thatâ€™s a conversion for your site.</p>\n<p>Now Google Analytics adds PayPal to referral traffic data because PayPal is the last site user visited before conversion. But the actual referral source is the affiliate website, not PayPal.</p>\n<p>In this way, PayPal takes the place of multiple referral source sites and prevents you from seeing the actual referrers. Thatâ€™s why you should exclude PayPal or any other third-party payment gateway from your referral list. Here&#8217;s how to do that:</p>\n<h3>1. Finding Your eCommerce Referrals in Google Analytics</h3>\n<p>Before adding PayPal to the Referral Exclusion List, itâ€™s best to check how many users are listed as referred by PayPal.</p>\n<p>To view your eCommerce referral list, youâ€™ll need to visit <strong>Acquisition Â» All Traffic Â» Referrals</strong> from your Google Analytics panel.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169255\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/view-referrals-ga-traffic.jpg\" alt=\"view-referrals-ga-traffic\" width=\"266\" height=\"584\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/view-referrals-ga-traffic.jpg 266w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/view-referrals-ga-traffic-137x300.jpg 137w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 266px) 100vw, 266px\" /></p>\n<p>Then click on <strong>eCommerce</strong> under the Explorer tab.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169256\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/referral-list-ga.jpg\" alt=\"referral-list-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"503\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/referral-list-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/referral-list-ga-300x243.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>As shown in the screenshot above, <strong>paypal.com</strong> made it to the top of the list. Thatâ€™s because all the referral traffic coming from multiple sources uses PayPal to make payments.</p>\n<h3>2. Adding PayPal to Referral Exclusion List in Google Analytics</h3>\n<p>To add PayPal to your referral exclusion list, youâ€™ll need to click theÂ <strong>Admin</strong> option at the bottom of the Analytics panel on the left.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169257\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin.jpg\" alt=\"ga-admin\" width=\"250\" height=\"586\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin.jpg 250w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-admin-128x300.jpg 128w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 250px) 100vw, 250px\" /></p>\n<p>Navigate to <strong>Tracking Info</strong> option in the <strong>Property</strong> section. Then, select <strong>Referral Exclusion List</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169258\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/referral-exclusion-list-ga.jpg\" alt=\"referral-exclusion-list-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"454\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/referral-exclusion-list-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/referral-exclusion-list-ga-300x220.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Upon clicking <strong>Referral Exclusion List</strong>, youâ€™ll see your list of excluded sites.</p>\n<p>Now all you need to do is to add paypal.com to the list. To do so, click theÂ <strong>Add Referral Exclusion</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169259\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/add-referral-exclusion.jpg\" alt=\"add-referral-exclusion\" width=\"620\" height=\"243\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/add-referral-exclusion.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/add-referral-exclusion-300x118.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, enter paypal.com to the domain box and click theÂ <strong>Create</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-169260\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/create-referral-exclusion-ga.jpg\" alt=\"create-referral-exclusion-ga\" width=\"523\" height=\"221\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/create-referral-exclusion-ga.jpg 523w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/create-referral-exclusion-ga-300x127.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 523px) 100vw, 523px\" /></p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s it! Now you can see paypal.com on the list.</p>\n<p>Now that youâ€™ve added PayPal to the referral exclusion list, Google Analytics will track the original referral sites and provide you with accurate referral traffic data.</p>\n<p>Google Analytics normally takes 24-48 hours to apply an exclusion. You can check your referral source data again after that time to check if the exclusion list is working for you.</p>\n<p>We hope this article helped you learn how to exclude PayPal from referral traffic data in Google Analytics. You may also want to learn <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-does-google-analytics-work-beginners-guide/\">how Google Analytics works</a>.</p>\n<p>Donâ€™t forget to follow us on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> for more helpful Google Analytics tips.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-paypal-to-referral-exclusion-list-in-google-analytics/\">How to Add PayPal to Referral Exclusion List in Google Analytics</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:102:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-paypal-to-referral-exclusion-list-in-google-analytics/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"How to Find and Use Real-Time Reports in Google Analytics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:175:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-find-real-time-reports-in-google-analytics/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=how-to-find-real-time-reports-in-google-analytics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:90:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-find-real-time-reports-in-google-analytics/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 05 Nov 2018 18:10:08 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"analytics reports\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:37:\"Real-Time Reports in Google Analytics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"MonsterInsights Real-Time reports\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=168689\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:644:\"<p>Wondering how to find Real-Time reports in Google Analytics? Real-Time reports allow you to monitor activity on your site right as its occurring. You can view the number of active users on your site at any given moment, their geographic locations, the pages theyâ€™re viewing, and more. Real-Time reports are really useful for marketers to [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-find-real-time-reports-in-google-analytics/\">How to Find and Use Real-Time Reports in Google Analytics</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Sunita Rai\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9470:\"<p>Wondering how to find Real-Time reports in Google Analytics? Real-Time reports allow you to monitor activity on your site right as its occurring. You can view the number of active users on your site at any given moment, their geographic locations, the pages theyâ€™re viewing, and more.</p>\n<p>Real-Time reports are really useful for marketers to track responses to marketing campaigns, product releases, and new articles. That&#8217;s why, in this article, weâ€™ll show you how to find Real-Time reports in Google Analytics and also share some tips on how to properly analyze and use them.</p>\n<h3>1. Find Google Analytics Real-Time Reports in Your WordPress Dashboard</h3>\n<p>Letâ€™s get started with the simplest way to find your Google Analytics Real-Time reports. If your site was built using WordPress, you can find your Google Analytics Real-Time reports right on your WordPress dashboard using <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\"> MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-157422\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg\" alt=\"monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress\" width=\"620\" height=\"250\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress-300x121.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\"> MonsterInsights</a> is the best Google Analytics plugin for WordPress. It allows you to install Google Analytics into WordPress sites easily with just a few clicks of your mouse, and provides you with comprehensive reports directly on your WordPress dashboard.</p>\n<p>But, first, you&#8217;ll need to <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/pricing/\">download the MonsterInsights plugin</a>, install it in your WordPress site, and set up Google Analytics with it. If you need detailed instructions, hereâ€™s our step-by-step guide on <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-properly-setup-google-analytics-in-wordpress/\">how to set up Google Analytics in WordPress with MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n<p>After youâ€™ve connected your WordPress site with Google Analytics, you can view your Google Analytics Real-time reports on your WordPress dashboard. Go to <strong>Insights Â» Reports</strong> from your WordPress dashboard and then click theÂ <strong>Real-Time</strong> tab.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-168691\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/how-to-find-real-time-reports-in-monsterinsights.jpg\" alt=\"how-to-find-real-time-reports-in-monsterinsights\" width=\"620\" height=\"432\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/how-to-find-real-time-reports-in-monsterinsights.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/how-to-find-real-time-reports-in-monsterinsights-300x209.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now you can find your siteâ€™s Real-Time reports, as shown in the example screenshot below:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-168692\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/real-time-report-in-monsterinsights.jpg\" alt=\"real-time-report-in-monsterinsights\" width=\"620\" height=\"415\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/real-time-report-in-monsterinsights.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/real-time-report-in-monsterinsights-300x201.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>The MonsterInsights Real-Time report includes the following information:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>The number of active users on your site right now</li>\n<li>Pageviews per minute for the past 30 minutes</li>\n<li>Top pages users are currently viewing on your site</li>\n<li>Top referral traffic sources for your site currently</li>\n<li>Top countries and cities visitors on your site right now are browsing from</li>\n</ol>\n<p>In some reports, like <strong>Top Pages </strong>andÂ <strong>Top Referral Traffic Sources</strong>, you&#8217;ll see a button to view all pageviews and referral traffic sources at the bottom. You can click on the button to view the full report on the Google Analytics platform.</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Real-Time reports feature was added in <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/announcing-monsterinsights-7-3-page-insights-addon-real-time-reports-and-more/\">MonsterInsights version 7.3.0</a>, so you need to have at least this version or later version installed on your WordPress site.</p>\n<h3>2. View Real-Time Reports in Your Google Analytics Account</h3>\n<p>If youâ€™ve installed <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-google-analytics-to-wordpress-without-a-plugin/\">Google Analytics in WordPress without a plugin</a>, you wonâ€™t find your Google Analytics data (including the Real-Time reports) in your WordPress dashboard. Instead, you&#8217;ll need to visit the official Google Analytics website and log into your Google Analytics account.</p>\n<p>Then, you can see theÂ <strong>Real-Time</strong> section on the left-hand side of theÂ <strong>Reports</strong> column. Simply click on it and then on the <strong>Overview</strong> submenu.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-168693\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/find-real-time-report-in-ga.jpg\" alt=\"find-real-time-report-in-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"415\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/find-real-time-report-in-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/find-real-time-report-in-ga-300x201.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now you can see the <strong>Overview</strong> report for your Real-Time data.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-168694\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-real-time-stats.jpg\" alt=\"ga-real-time-stats\" width=\"540\" height=\"323\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-real-time-stats.jpg 540w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-real-time-stats-300x179.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 540px) 100vw, 540px\" /></p>\n<p>In the Real-Time Overview report, you can see the following data:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Active users on site right now</li>\n<li>Pageviews per minute for the last 30 minutes</li>\n<li>Division of current traffic based on different devices theyâ€™re using</li>\n<li>Top referrals for the current active users on site</li>\n<li>Top social traffic</li>\n<li>Top keywords</li>\n<li>Top active pages users on your site right now are viewing</li>\n<li>Top locations on the Google map</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To view more data in the Real-Time reports, you can click the submenus below the <strong>Overview</strong> submenu in the <strong>Real-Time</strong> section.</p>\n<h3>How to Properly Analyze and Use the Real-Time Reports</h3>\n<p>The Real-Time reports in Google Analytics are very important for website owners. These reports can give you really insightful information and data to analyze your marketing campaigns and grow your business.</p>\n<p>Letâ€™s discuss 3 of the major benefits of using Real-Time reports.</p>\n<p>1. You can track active users on your site right now. Keeping eyes on the Real-Time reports at different times throughout a day lets you find out what time your site is most visited. Then, you can publish major announcements, product releases, and blog articles during that time of the day for more visibility.</p>\n<p>2. You can track the results of your marketing efforts as they happen. Itâ€™s useful for tracking how your email marketing, social media marketing, and other paid marketing campaigns are performing.</p>\n<p>With the Real-Time reports, you donâ€™t need to wait until a later date to see how users are reacting to your marketing campaigns and new product.</p>\n<p>3. Next, referral traffic sources and top places data in the Real-Time reports will help you to decide where to concentrate your marketing efforts and at what time. When you know the actual locations where most visitors on your site are coming, you can improve your marketing campaigns by making them specific to those locations and time zones.</p>\n<p>Hence, Google Analytics Real-Time reports help you improve your website marketing and grow your business.</p>\n<p>We hope this article helped you learn how to find Real-Time reports in Google Analytics and how to use them. You may also want to learn <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-a-stats-dashboard-on-your-wordpress-site/\">how to add a stats dashboard on your WordPress site</a>.</p>\n<p>Donâ€™t forget to follow us on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> for more helpful Google Analytics tips.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-find-real-time-reports-in-google-analytics/\">How to Find and Use Real-Time Reports in Google Analytics</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:87:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-find-real-time-reports-in-google-analytics/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:59:\"How to Check Stats for Individual WordPress Posts and Pages\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:195:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-check-stats-for-individual-wordpress-posts-and-pages/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=how-to-check-stats-for-individual-wordpress-posts-and-pages\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:100:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-check-stats-for-individual-wordpress-posts-and-pages/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 01 Nov 2018 20:37:49 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:24:\"Google Analytics metrics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"page insights\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:43:\"view stats for each individual page or post\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=168225\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:637:\"<p>Want to check stats for individual WordPress posts and pages? Great idea! When you know how your individual posts and pages are performing, you can optimize each of them to boost your site&#8217;s conversions. Google Analytics is a powerful tool you can use to track the performance of your posts and pages precisely. In this [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-check-stats-for-individual-wordpress-posts-and-pages/\">How to Check Stats for Individual WordPress Posts and Pages</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Sunita Rai\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12209:\"<p>Want to check stats for individual WordPress posts and pages? Great idea! When you know how your individual posts and pages are performing, you can optimize each of them to boost your site&#8217;s conversions. Google Analytics is a powerful tool you can use to track the performance of your posts and pages precisely.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâ€™ll show you how to see stats for each individual post or page in WordPress (step-by-step).</p>\n<h3>Step 1. Set up Google Analytics on Your WordPress Site</h3>\n<p>First of all, you&#8217;ll have to install and set up Google Analytics on your WordPress site. Google Analytics is the most popular digital analytics tool to track your website visitors and their behavior on your site, and provides you with detailed data.</p>\n<p>For WordPress sites, itâ€™s easy to set up and use Google Analytics with the help of theÂ <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights plugin</a>.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-157422\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg\" alt=\"monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress\" width=\"620\" height=\"250\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress-300x121.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p>MonsterInsights simplifies the entire process of installing the Analytics code in WordPress as well as viewing your important website data because you can <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/feature/google-analytics-dashboard/\">see the highly comprehensive reports right inside your WordPress dashboard</a>. Besides, it allows you to easily set up tracking advanced metrics like <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/addon/ecommerce/\">eCommerce tracking</a>, <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/addon/forms/\">forms conversions</a>, <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/addon/ads/\">Google ads tracking</a>, <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/feature/file-download-tracking/\">file downloads</a>, etc.</p>\n<p>To get started, <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/pricing/\">download MonsterInsights&#8217; plugin file</a> on your computer and install it in WordPress. Then, youâ€™ll need to connect your Google Analytics account with your WordPress site. It takes just a few clicks!</p>\n<p>If you need detailed instructions, hereâ€™s our step-by-step guide on <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-properly-setup-google-analytics-in-wordpress/\">how to set up Google Analytics in WordPress with MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n<h3>Step 2. Install and Activate the Page Insights Addon</h3>\n<p>To allow you track your individual WordPress posts and pages, MonsterInsights comes with a great addon:Â <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/addon/page-insights/\">Page Insights</a>. The addon lets you view the stats for each of your WordPress blog posts and pages directly in your dashboard.</p>\n<p>You can install the addon by visiting theÂ <strong>Insights Â» Addons</strong> page from your WordPress dashboard.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-168226\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/install-monsterinsights-page-insights-addon.jpg\" alt=\"install-monsterinsights-page-insights-addon\" width=\"405\" height=\"480\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/install-monsterinsights-page-insights-addon.jpg 405w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/install-monsterinsights-page-insights-addon-253x300.jpg 253w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 405px) 100vw, 405px\" /></p>\n<p>After itâ€™s installed, youâ€™ll see the addonâ€™s status asÂ <strong>Inactive</strong>. Next, click the <strong>Activate</strong> button to enable the addon.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-168234\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/activate-monsterinsights-page-insights-addon.jpg\" alt=\"activate-monsterinsights-page-insights-addon\" width=\"405\" height=\"567\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/activate-monsterinsights-page-insights-addon.jpg 405w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/activate-monsterinsights-page-insights-addon-214x300.jpg 214w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 405px) 100vw, 405px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, the addonâ€™s status isÂ <strong>Active</strong>.</p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s it! Now, you can see the stats for your individual WordPress posts and pages right out of the box.</p>\n<h3>Step 3. Viewing Stats for Individual Posts and Pages in WordPress</h3>\n<p>Once youâ€™ve installed and activated MonsterInsights&#8217; Page Insights addon properly in WordPress, you can check stats for each blog post and page in WordPress easily.</p>\n<p>To view the stats for your individual posts, youâ€™ll need to visit <strong>Posts Â» All Posts</strong> from your dashboard. Similarly, youâ€™ll need to go to <strong>Pages Â» All Pages</strong> to view the stats for your individual pages.</p>\n<p>Now, you can see an <strong>Insights</strong> column added on your WordPress Posts/ Pages screen.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-168238\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/pages-screen-with-insights-icon.jpg\" alt=\"pages-screen-with-insights-icon\" width=\"620\" height=\"222\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/pages-screen-with-insights-icon.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/pages-screen-with-insights-icon-300x107.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, click on the Insights icon next to a blog post or page to view the stats for the specific blog post or page.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-168227\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/page-insights-icon-click.jpg\" alt=\"page-insights-icon-click\" width=\"620\" height=\"288\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/page-insights-icon-click.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/page-insights-icon-click-300x139.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>You&#8217;ll see a popup window with stats for the individual blog post or page.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-168228\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/monsterinsights-page-insights-reports.jpg\" alt=\"monsterinsights-page-insights-reports\" width=\"620\" height=\"370\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/monsterinsights-page-insights-reports.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/monsterinsights-page-insights-reports-300x179.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>The Page Insights report allows you to quickly view the following important metrics:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Bounce Rate</strong>: The percentage of single-page sessions in which users view only a single page and exit your site without triggering any other request to the Analytics server.</li>\n<li><strong>Entrances</strong>: The number of times users enter your website through the specific blog post or page.</li>\n<li><strong>Page Views</strong>: The total number of views for the specific blog post or page.</li>\n<li><strong>Time on Page</strong>: The average time users spend on the specific blog post or page.</li>\n<li><strong>Page Load Time</strong>: The average time it takes to load the specific blog post or page.</li>\n<li><strong>Exits</strong>: The number of times users exit your website through the specific post or page.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Now that you can view the key metrics for each individual blog post or page from your WordPress dashboard, you can easily identify which posts and pages are doing well and which need optimization. Then, you can optimize the low-performing pages or posts to boost user engagement and conversions.</p>\n<h3>Viewing Stats for Individual Posts or Pages from Your Google Analytics Account</h3>\n<p>Alternatively, you can view stats for individual posts or pages from your Google Analytics account. This method may be best for users whoâ€™re already intimately familiar with the Google Analytics platform.</p>\n<p>First, youâ€™ll need to log into your Google Analytics account. Then, go to <strong>Behavior Â» Site Content Â» All Pages</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-168246\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-all-pages-report.jpg\" alt=\"ga-all-pages-report\" width=\"620\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-all-pages-report.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/ga-all-pages-report-300x206.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>There, you&#8217;ll see the stats for your individual pages and posts. As withÂ <strong>Page Insights</strong> reports, you can see the important metrics like pageviews, unique pageviews, average time on page, entrances, bounce rate, exit rate, and page value.</p>\n<p>On the first page, youâ€™ll see the top 10 pages and posts. To view more pages and posts, you can click the pagination arrows at the bottom.</p>\n<p>This way, you can easily view your top performing posts and pages but you&#8217;ll need to view almost all the pages to find the least performing pages and posts by clicking on one page after another.</p>\n<p>However, thereâ€™s a search option to directly find stats for a specific page or post.</p>\n<p>First, youâ€™ll need to copy the slug for the page or post. A slug is the part of a URL that identifies a specific post or page. Itâ€™s often the last part of a URL, which is editable.</p>\n<p>For example, letâ€™s take this URL (<strong>https://www.monsterinsights.com/google-analytics-plugin/</strong>).</p>\n<p>Here, <strong>/google-analytics-plugin/</strong> is the slug.</p>\n<p>So, copy the slug of the specific page or post and paste it in the search box of your Google Analytics reports page.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-168244\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/search-stats-for-one-page-ga.jpg\" alt=\"search-stats-for-one-page-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"136\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/search-stats-for-one-page-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/search-stats-for-one-page-ga-300x66.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, you can see the stats for the specific page or post.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-168245\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/view-individual-post-stats-ga.jpg\" alt=\"view-individual-post-stats-ga\" width=\"620\" height=\"200\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/view-individual-post-stats-ga.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/view-individual-post-stats-ga-300x97.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s it!</p>\n<p>We hope this article helped you to learn how to check stats for individual WordPress posts and pages with Google Analytics. You may also want to learn <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-a-stats-dashboard-on-your-wordpress-site/\">how to add a stats dashboard on your WordPress site</a>.</p>\n<p>Donâ€™t forget to follow us on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> for more helpful Google Analytics tips.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-check-stats-for-individual-wordpress-posts-and-pages/\">How to Check Stats for Individual WordPress Posts and Pages</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:97:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-check-stats-for-individual-wordpress-posts-and-pages/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:83:\"Announcing MonsterInsights 7.3 – Page Insights Addon, Real Time Reports, and More\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:231:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/announcing-monsterinsights-7-3-page-insights-addon-real-time-reports-and-more/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=announcing-monsterinsights-7-3-page-insights-addon-real-time-reports-and-more\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:118:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/announcing-monsterinsights-7-3-page-insights-addon-real-time-reports-and-more/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 30 Oct 2018 09:37:10 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Announcements\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=167791\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:711:\"<p>Today, I&#8217;m super excited to announce the release of MonsterInsights 7.3 because it comes with a lot of exciting features that you have been asking for including real-time reports, page insights addon, and more. Let&#8217;s take a look at what&#8217;s new in MonsterInsights 7.3&#8230; Page Insights Addon Want to see stats for each individual blog [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/announcing-monsterinsights-7-3-page-insights-addon-real-time-reports-and-more/\">Announcing MonsterInsights 7.3 &#8211; Page Insights Addon, Real Time Reports, and More</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"Syed Balkhi\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5730:\"<p>Today, I&#8217;m super excited to announce the release of MonsterInsights 7.3 because it comes with a lot of exciting features that you have been asking for including real-time reports, page insights addon, and more.</p>\n<p>Let&#8217;s take a look at what&#8217;s new in MonsterInsights 7.3&#8230;</p>\n<h3>Page Insights Addon</h3>\n<p>Want to see stats for each individual blog post or page in WordPress?</p>\n<p>Our new Page Insights addon allows you to quickly view individual post / page metrics right from your WordPress dashboard.</p>\n<p>Once activated, the page insights addon will add an Insights column on the WordPress Posts / Pages screen.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167361\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/how-to-find-page-insights.png\" alt=\"How to Find Page Insights\" width=\"1200\" height=\"557\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/how-to-find-page-insights.png 1200w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/how-to-find-page-insights-300x139.png 300w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/how-to-find-page-insights-768x356.png 768w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/how-to-find-page-insights-1024x475.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" /></p>\n<p>When you click on the Insights icon, it will open a popup window with stats for the individual blog post or page.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167364\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/page-insights.png\" alt=\"MonsterInsights Page Insights\" width=\"1200\" height=\"744\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/page-insights.png 1200w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/page-insights-300x186.png 300w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/page-insights-768x476.png 768w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/page-insights-1024x635.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" /></p>\n<p>The Page Insights addon allows you to quickly view important metrics like: new visitors, page views, bounce rate, time on page, page load time, and exits.</p>\n<h3>Real Time Reports</h3>\n<p>We have also added the much requested Real-Time report in MonsterInsights.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167923\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/real-time-report.png\" alt=\"MonsterInsights Real Time Report Screenshot\" width=\"1200\" height=\"801\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/real-time-report.png 1200w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/real-time-report-300x200.png 300w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/real-time-report-768x513.png 768w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/real-time-report-1024x684.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" /></p>\n<p>This report allows you to see the results of your marketing campaign or product launch as it&#8217;s happening.</p>\n<p>You can track the number of active visitors, top referral sources, top countries, and top pages right from the Real-time report.</p>\n<p>Because real-time reports can really impact Google Analytics API quota, we have it set to refresh every 60 seconds.</p>\n<h3>Custom Link Attribution</h3>\n<p>Want to measure results of the most important links on your website?</p>\n<p>With MonsterInsights&#8217; new custom link attribution feature, you can easily add custom event tracking to your important links and call-to-action buttons.</p>\n<p>To add custom event tracking to your WordPress links, simply add the following data-variable tags to the HTML of your link:</p>\n<p><strong>&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.monsterinsights.com&quot; data-vars-ga-category=&quot;Custom Category&quot; data-vars-ga-action=&quot;Custom Action&quot; data-vars-ga-label=&quot;Custom Label&quot;&gt;Example&lt;/a&gt;</strong></p>\n<p>This will add event tracking to the specific link, so you can track how valuable this link is when it comes Ecommerce or other conversion metrics.</p>\n<p>We also updated our Google AMP addon to add support for custom event tracking, so you can easily measure results while still utilizing the performance improvements of Google AMP.</p>\n<h3>Gravity Forms and Formidable Forms Conversion Tracking</h3>\n<p>We have also updated our <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/addon/forms/\">Forms Tracking addon</a> to add improved conversion tracking support for both Gravity Forms and Formidable Forms.</p>\n<p>While our Forms Tracking addon works with all <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/best-wordpress-contact-form-plugins/\">popular WordPress form plugins</a>, improved support helps you better identify and track your form conversions, so you can grow your business.</p>\n<p>We hope you enjoy these features. We have a lot more in the works that I can&#8217;t wait to share with you in the upcoming weeks.</p>\n<p>As always, thank you for continued support of MonsterInsights. We look forward to continue making analytics easy for you!</p>\n<p><em>Syed and the MonsterInsights team</em></p>\n<p>Don&#8217;t have a MonsterInsights Pro license? <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/pricing/\">Click here to get started today</a>, and experience the power, and ease, of MonsterInsights.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/announcing-monsterinsights-7-3-page-insights-addon-real-time-reports-and-more/\">Announcing MonsterInsights 7.3 &#8211; Page Insights Addon, Real Time Reports, and More</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:115:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/announcing-monsterinsights-7-3-page-insights-addon-real-time-reports-and-more/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"How to Share Your Google Analytics Reports with Others\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:185:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-share-your-google-analytics-reports-with-others/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=how-to-share-your-google-analytics-reports-with-others\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:95:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-share-your-google-analytics-reports-with-others/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 29 Oct 2018 15:00:43 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"analytics reports\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"traffic report\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:22:\"sharing Analytics data\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=167675\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:615:\"<p>Do you want to learn how to share your Google Analytics reports with others? Sharing solid data is a great way to gain the trust of customers and potential business partners! But, since they arenâ€™t your team yet, you may not want to grant them access to your Analytics account. However, you can still share [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-share-your-google-analytics-reports-with-others/\">How to Share Your Google Analytics Reports with Others</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Sunita Rai\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10056:\"<p>Do you want to learn how to share your Google Analytics reports with others? Sharing solid data is a great way to gain the trust of customers and potential business partners! But, since they arenâ€™t your team yet, you may not want to grant them access to your Analytics account. However, you can still share your desired Analytics reports with them if you&#8217;re in the know.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâ€™ll show you how to share your Google Analytics reports with others without allowing them access to your Analytics account. Trust us: it&#8217;s super easy!</p>\n<h3>Why Would You Want to Share Your Google Analytics Data?</h3>\n<p>Showing solid statistics and data is one of the most effective ways to convince people over to your side. When trying to sell a product, you can more quickly convert a potential customer into a buyer if you show them how many people are already using your product (and for how long). Put simply: sharing your detail-rich Analytics data can help you sell more.</p>\n<p>Similarly, if youâ€™re planning any kind of partnership with another company, they&#8217;ll most likely ask you to share your Analytics reports with them. By sharing Analytics data, they can properly evaluate your businesses and make a more-informed partnership deal. Plus, if your Analytics are awesome, showing them off to potential partners will ensure that they don&#8217;t undervalue your business when money gets put on the table.</p>\n<p>However, when youâ€™re sharing Analytics data with other people outside of your team members, itâ€™s best not to <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-grant-access-to-your-account-and-share-google-analytics-reports/\">grant access to your Analytics account</a>. This is because you donâ€™t want to share every report. Instead, you should only relevant reports from a specified time period to get your business ahead.</p>\n<p>Now, letâ€™s go ahead and see how to share Google Analytics reports with others hassle-free.</p>\n<h3>1. Export Analytics Data in PDF, Google Sheets, Excel, or CSV</h3>\n<p>The first option to share your Google Analytics data is to export a report in a PDF, Google Sheets, Excel, or CSV format. Then, you can share the file by uploading it to a Google Drive folder or directly via email.</p>\n<p>To get started, youâ€™ll need to log into your Google Analytics account. Then, navigate to a report you want to share. In the top right corner, you&#8217;ll find anÂ <strong>Export</strong> option for almost every report in Google Analytics.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167740\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/export-option-ga-reports.jpg\" alt=\"export-option-ga-reports\" width=\"620\" height=\"292\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/export-option-ga-reports.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/export-option-ga-reports-300x141.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Click on the <strong>Export</strong> option and select the file type youâ€™d like to export.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167741\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/choose-file-type-export-ga-reports.jpg\" alt=\"choose-file-type-export-ga-reports\" width=\"620\" height=\"201\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/choose-file-type-export-ga-reports.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/choose-file-type-export-ga-reports-300x97.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, itâ€™ll automatically download the report onto your computer. Now you can share the report with your customers or partners easily by emailing it to them or by sharing a Google Drive folder.</p>\n<p>If youâ€™re <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-properly-setup-google-analytics-in-wordpress/\">using Google Analytics in your WordPress site with MonsterInsights</a>, you can see your Analytics reports inside your WordPress dashboard. If you&#8217;d like to share any report from the dashboard reports, you can click the <strong>View All Report</strong> below the reports which will automatically take you to your Google Analytics account.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167742\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/view-full-report-monsterinsights-reports.jpg\" alt=\"view-full-report-monsterinsights-reports\" width=\"620\" height=\"374\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/view-full-report-monsterinsights-reports.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/view-full-report-monsterinsights-reports-300x181.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, simply follow the same process discussed above.</p>\n<h3>2. How to Share Your Google Analytics Reports on a Regular Basis</h3>\n<p>The next option is to share your Analytics reports by setting up automatic emails in Google Analytics. With this option, you can schedule automatic emails containing the Analytics reports daily, weekly, or monthly.</p>\n<p>This is useful for sharing your Analytics data with your customers, partners, and team members for a certain period of time on a regular basis.</p>\n<p>You can find aÂ <strong>Share</strong> option next to <strong>Export</strong> for almost every Analytics data report. Click the <strong>Share</strong> option to get started.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167743\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/share-option-ga-reports.jpg\" alt=\"share-option-ga-reports\" width=\"620\" height=\"165\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/share-option-ga-reports.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/share-option-ga-reports-300x80.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, enter the email addresses you want to share your Analytics report with. Next, you can review the subject line and rephrase it or leave it as it is. Next, confirm the attachment type. Itâ€™s PDF by default, but you can change it to an Excel or CSV file if you desire.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167744\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/sharing-ga-reports-via-emai.jpg\" alt=\"sharing-ga-reports-via-emai\" width=\"620\" height=\"541\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/sharing-ga-reports-via-emai.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/sharing-ga-reports-via-emai-300x262.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>After that, you can choose the frequency of the emails. Also, you can choose which day you want to send out emails for the weekly and monthly options.</p>\n<p>Then, in the <strong>Advanced Options</strong>, you can choose how long a duration you want to send the emails.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167745\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/advanced-options-sharing-ga-reports-via-email.jpg\" alt=\"advanced-options-sharing-ga-reports-via-email\" width=\"620\" height=\"378\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/advanced-options-sharing-ga-reports-via-email.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/advanced-options-sharing-ga-reports-via-email-300x183.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, insert the email body with some lines about why the receiver is getting the email. Finally, check the <strong>Iâ€™m not a robot</strong>Â box and click theÂ <strong>Send</strong> button. Youâ€™ll see a quick notification stating that your email has been scheduled.</p>\n<p>If you want to add more reports to the same email, you can easily do so. First, youâ€™ll need to find the report you want to add and click the <strong>Share</strong> option, same as before. Then, click <strong>Add to an existing email</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167746\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-to-an-existing-email-sharing-ga-reports.jpg\" alt=\"add-to-an-existing-email-sharing-ga-reports\" width=\"620\" height=\"378\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-to-an-existing-email-sharing-ga-reports.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-to-an-existing-email-sharing-ga-reports-300x183.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now you can select which existing email you want to add the report to.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167748\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-to-an-existing-email.jpg\" alt=\"add-to-an-existing-email\" width=\"620\" height=\"241\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-to-an-existing-email.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-to-an-existing-email-300x117.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Finally, donâ€™t forget to click the <strong>Save</strong> button.</p>\n<p>We hope this article helped you to learn how to share your Google Analytic reports with others. You may also want to learn <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-create-custom-reports-in-google-analytics-step-by-step/\">how to create custom reports in Google Analytics</a>.</p>\n<p>Donâ€™t forget to follow us on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> for more helpful Google Analytics tips.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-share-your-google-analytics-reports-with-others/\">How to Share Your Google Analytics Reports with Others</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:92:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-share-your-google-analytics-reports-with-others/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:47:\"5 Best WordPress Ad Management Plugins for 2018\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:149:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/best-wordpress-ad-management-plugins/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=best-wordpress-ad-management-plugins\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:77:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/best-wordpress-ad-management-plugins/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 25 Oct 2018 14:16:17 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Marketing\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"ads tracking\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:28:\"google adsense for WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"add advertisements to WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=167146\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:608:\"<p>Are you looking for the best WordPress ad management plugins? Adding advertisements is one of the most common ways to monetize a website. With the right ad management plugin, you can properly manage your WordPress ads and boost your revenue. In this article, weâ€™ll share the 5 best ad management plugins for WordPress so you [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/best-wordpress-ad-management-plugins/\">5 Best WordPress Ad Management Plugins for 2018</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Sunita Rai\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13114:\"<p>Are you looking for the best WordPress ad management plugins? Adding advertisements is one of the most common ways to monetize a website. With the right ad management plugin, you can properly manage your WordPress ads and boost your revenue.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâ€™ll share the 5 best ad management plugins for WordPress so you can optimize your earnings from advertisements.</p>\n<h3>Why Use a WordPress Ad Management Plugin?</h3>\n<p>If youâ€™re looking for an easy way to earn money through your site, adding adverts is a cool option. Many WordPress themes nowadays are advertisement-ready; however, they lack proper ad management features. Thatâ€™s where an ad management plugin comes handy.</p>\n<p>For an instance, if you want to <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-add-google-adsense-to-your-wordpress-site/\">add Google AdSense ads in WordPress</a>, you can use aÂ <strong>Custom HTML</strong> widget in WordPress. This method is simple, but you cannot place ads on areas other than your themeâ€™s widget-ready areas. An ad management plugin helps you insert ads anywhere on your site.</p>\n<p>Plus, ad management plugins allow you to add both direct ads and AdSense ads on your site. You can start rotating and scheduling your ads to automate their displays. This helps you save plenty of time for more important tasks.</p>\n<p>In a nutshell, ad management plugins help you create better ads, manage the ads properly, and increase your earnings.</p>\n<p>Now, letâ€™s go ahead and check out the best ad management plugins for WordPress.</p>\n<h3><a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/refer/adsanity/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">1. AdSanity</a></h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/refer/adsanity/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-162110\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/adsanity-wordpress-ad-manag.jpg\" alt=\"adsanity-wordpress-ad-manag\" width=\"620\" height=\"315\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/adsanity-wordpress-ad-manag.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/adsanity-wordpress-ad-manag-300x152.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p>AdSanity is the best WordPress ad management plugin available on the market. Itâ€™s a simple and easy-to-use plugin with powerful options to fully control and manage your WordPress ads.</p>\n<p>Using AdSanity, you can insert self-hosted direct ads as well as network ads like Google AdSense on your WordPress site easily. Not to mention, you can place your ads anywhere on your site using widgets, shortcodes, or template tags.</p>\n<p>The plugin also allows you to group ads based on categories, run a single ad or ad group, and schedule ads on your WordPress site. The plugin is extensible with a set of cool addons ready for use. If you need an extra feature, you can always look up to the available addons.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/refer/adsanity/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Get started with AdSanity today!</a></p>\n<h3><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/adrotate/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">2. AdRotate</a></h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/adrotate/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167160\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/adrotate-wordpress-plugin.jpg\" alt=\"adrotate-wordpress-plugin\" width=\"620\" height=\"202\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/adrotate-wordpress-plugin.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/adrotate-wordpress-plugin-300x98.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p>AdRotate allows you to easily create ads and ad groups and add them to your WordPress site. You can insert ads into your WordPress posts using shortcodes and into the sidebars using widgets.</p>\n<p>The plugin offers a simple interface to create and manage ads. Itâ€™s designed to match the WordPress dashboard interface, so you can easily get familiar with it. It supports both custom-made ads and ads from servers like Media.net and Google AdSense.</p>\n<p>The AdRotate plugin is available in both free and premium versions. If you want advanced features like geo-targeting, Adblock disguise, mobile adverts, and media/ asset management, youâ€™ll need to install the pro version of the plugin.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/adrotate/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Get started with AdRotate today!</a></p>\n<h3><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/insert-post-ads/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">3. Insert Post Ads</a></h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/insert-post-ads/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167161\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/insert-post-ads-wordpress-plugin.jpg\" alt=\"insert-post-ads-wordpress-plugin\" width=\"620\" height=\"229\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/insert-post-ads-wordpress-plugin.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/insert-post-ads-wordpress-plugin-300x111.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Insert Post Ads allows you to automatically insert Google AdSense or any network ads into your blog posts. Displaying ads in your blog articles helps to increase click-through rates (CTRs) and boost your earnings.</p>\n<p>With Insert Post Ads plugin, you can automatically display ads before content, after post content, or after a specified number of paragraphs. Therefore, you donâ€™t need to manually insert ads into every piece of content. You can add the ads to your WordPress posts, pages, and custom post types.</p>\n<p>The plugin is simple and easy-to-use. Anyone can quickly set up the plugin and start adding advertisements. It supports Google AdSense or any advertising codes.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/insert-post-ads/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Get started with Insert Post Ads today!</a></p>\n<h3><a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/refer/oiopublisher/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">4. OIO Publisher</a></h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/refer/oiopublisher/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167162\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/oio-publisher-advertising-tool-wordpress.jpg\" alt=\"oio-publisher-advertising-tool-wordpress\" width=\"620\" height=\"295\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/oio-publisher-advertising-tool-wordpress.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/oio-publisher-advertising-tool-wordpress-300x143.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p>OIO Publisher is great for small businesses who want to sell ad spots directly to advertisers. It allows you to create ad spots on different locations on your site with <strong>Advertise here</strong> default text where advertisers can click to buy the spot.</p>\n<p>After the advertisers click on the banner, theyâ€™ll be taken to the sales page. From there, they can create an ad, pay for the ad spot, and display their ad. The advertisers can choose how long a period they want to show the ad. Thisâ€™ll eliminate a middlemanâ€™s involvement in displaying ads on your site.</p>\n<p>The plugin handles payments for you and advertisers. It also sends daily advertisement reports to the advertisers that include the number of clicks, impressions, CTR, etc.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/refer/oiopublisher/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Get started with OIO Publisher today!</a></p>\n<h3><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/ad-inserter/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">5. Ad Inserter</a></h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/ad-inserter/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-167163\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/ad-inserter-wordpress-plugin.jpg\" alt=\"ad-inserter-wordpress-plugin\" width=\"620\" height=\"196\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/ad-inserter-wordpress-plugin.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/ad-inserter-wordpress-plugin-300x95.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Ad Inserter is a feature-rich plugin with plenty of options to create ads and insert into your WordPress site. It supports all types of ads including Google AdSense, Amazon Native Shopping Ads, Media.net ads, and rotating banner ads.</p>\n<p>The plugin allows you to display ads in multiple locations on your site like before or after a post, before or after a paragraph, before or after comments, before or after a post excerpt, etc. Once configured, the plugin automatically inserts ads into posts and pages; however, you can disable automatic insertion anytime.</p>\n<p>You can find this plugin both in free and premium licenses. The free version is decent with a set of useful features, but youâ€™ll probably want to upgrade your license for more advanced options.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/ad-inserter/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Get started with Ad Inserter today!</a></p>\n<h3>Tracking the Performance of Your Ads with Google Analytics</h3>\n<p>WordPress ad management plugins provide you with cool options to manage your ads; however, most of them fail to provide proper tracking features. So, we recommend you use theÂ <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a> plugin for ads tracking.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-157422\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg\" alt=\"monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress\" width=\"620\" height=\"250\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress-300x121.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p>By tracking the performance of your ads, you can learn exactly how your site&#8217;s visitors interact with your ads and then optimize your ads for more revenue.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a> is the most powerful Google Analytics plugin for WordPress. It helps you to track your website&#8217;s audience and their behaviors on your site using Google Analytics. The plugin comes with a powerful <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/addon/ads/\">Ads Tracking addon</a> to let you track the performance of your AdSense ads properly.</p>\n<p>With MonsterInsights&#8217; ads tracking, you can track click-through rates to see how many clicks each banner ad is receiving. Then, you can identify the most popular ads on your site as well as the worst performing ones. You can delete the less popular ads or replace them with more relevant ads. This helps to improve CTR and boost your revenue.</p>\n<p>To get started, youâ€™ll need to <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-properly-setup-google-analytics-in-wordpress/\">install MonsterInsights and set it up in your WordPress site</a>. Then, youâ€™ll need to install the Ads Tracking addon and enable Google AdSense tracking.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-89954\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/activate-ads-addon.jpg\" alt=\"activate ads addon\" width=\"379\" height=\"474\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/activate-ads-addon.jpg 379w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/activate-ads-addon-240x300.jpg 240w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 379px) 100vw, 379px\" /></p>\n<p>For detailed instructions, check out our step-by-step guide on <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-track-adsense-in-google-analytics-to-optimize-your-revenue/\">how to track AdSense in Google Analytics</a>.</p>\n<p>We hope this article helped you to find the best ad management plugins for WordPress. You may also like to read our post on theÂ <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/the-highest-earning-google-adsense-ad-placements/\">highest earning Google AdSense ad placements</a>.</p>\n<p>Also, donâ€™t forget to follow us on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> for more Google Analytics tutorials.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/best-wordpress-ad-management-plugins/\">5 Best WordPress Ad Management Plugins for 2018</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:74:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/best-wordpress-ad-management-plugins/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:56:\"How to Block WordPress Referrer Spam in Google Analytics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:175:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/block-wordpress-referrer-spam-in-google-analytics/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=block-wordpress-referrer-spam-in-google-analytics\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:90:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/block-wordpress-referrer-spam-in-google-analytics/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 22 Oct 2018 13:15:14 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:24:\"google analytics filters\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:35:\"blocking referrer spam in wordpress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:21:\"google analytics spam\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/?p=165570\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:634:\"<p>Are you receiving a lot of referral traffic from sites with unusual domains? If the bounce rate for those hits is 100% and session duration is 00.00.00, it&#8217;s most likely referrer spam. Referrer spam can distort your analytics reports and harm your site. In this article, weâ€™ll show you how to block WordPress referrer spam [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/block-wordpress-referrer-spam-in-google-analytics/\">How to Block WordPress Referrer Spam in Google Analytics</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Sunita Rai\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15903:\"<p>Are you receiving a lot of referral traffic from sites with unusual domains? If the bounce rate for those hits is 100% and session duration is 00.00.00, it&#8217;s most likely referrer spam. Referrer spam can distort your analytics reports and harm your site.</p>\n<p>In this article, weâ€™ll show you how to block WordPress referrer spam in Google Analytics.</p>\n<h3>Not Using Google Analytics Yet?</h3>\n<p>If youâ€™re wondering what this article is about, or what Google Analytics is, we recommend you take a moment to check out why Google Analytics is <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/why-your-business-needs-google-analytics-starting-right-now/\">important for your business growth</a>.</p>\n<p>To put it in brief here: Google Analytics is the most popular website analytics tool available on the market. It allows you to track your website&#8217;s traffic and provides you with detailed reports on how users interact with your site. You can view where your site visitors are coming from, what pages they open on your site, what they click, and everything else you could ever want to know right from the Analytics reports.</p>\n<p>And, once you know all that information, you can make informed marketing decisions to grow your site.</p>\n<p>In WordPress, itâ€™s easy to set up and use Google Analytics with the <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a> plugin.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-157422\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg\" alt=\"monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress\" width=\"620\" height=\"250\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/monsterinsights-best-ga-plugin-for-wordpress-300x121.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\">MonsterInsights</a> is the best and most user-friendly Google Analytics plugin for WordPress. It&#8217;s easy to use and comes packed with powerful features to allow you to track all your important analytics data. Using the plugin, you can easily track advanced metrics like eCommerce data, ads, forms, etc. And, you can see all the <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/feature/google-analytics-dashboard/\">reports right in your WordPress dashboard</a>.</p>\n<p>It takes zero effort to set up Google Analytics in WordPress when using this plugin. For detailed instructions, hereâ€™s our complete guide on <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-properly-setup-google-analytics-in-wordpress/\">how to set up Google Analytics in WordPress</a>. If you want to learn more, you can explore other useful articles on our blog.</p>\n<p>Now, letâ€™s see what referrer spam actually is, and how to block WordPress referrer spam in Google Analytics.</p>\n<h3>What&#8217;s Referrer Spam?</h3>\n<p>Referrer spam is a way to pass fake website hits to your Google Analytics. Youâ€™ll receive referrer spam in your analytics reports when a spammer website sends out multiple requests to your site with fake URLs. Then, Google Analytics tracks the fake hits as valid referral traffic and prepares reports.</p>\n<p>Due to the referrer spam attack, there can be a massive increase in your regular website traffic. But those visits arenâ€™t from humans; they&#8217;re from bots sent out by a spammer. Sometimes, the bots bypass your site and hit the Google Analytics servers directly. Such hits also appear as referral traffic in your analytics reports. That kind of spam is called ghost referral spam.</p>\n<p>Identifying referral spam in your Google Analytics reports is quite simple though. First, you&#8217;ll need to find out your referral traffic in Google Analytics. Open your Google Analytics account and navigate to <strong>Acquisition Â» All Traffic Â» Referrals</strong> to see your referrers.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-165576\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/referral-spam-ganalytics-ov.jpg\" alt=\"referral-spam-ganalytics-ov\" width=\"620\" height=\"262\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/referral-spam-ganalytics-ov.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/referral-spam-ganalytics-ov-300x127.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>You can suspect the strange and unusual domain names. Then, you can check the bounce rate. If the bounce rate is 100% and average session duration 00.00.00, these links can be spammy links.</p>\n<p>Now, letâ€™s see how referrer spam can harm your website.</p>\n<h3>Why You Need to Worry About Referrer Spam?</h3>\n<p>One common purpose of referral spam is search engine optimization. The spammer website sends out the fake referrer URL to thousands of websites, and when they appear in the analytics reports, some are likely to click the links. Then, it increases the clicks on those links and can impact the spammer websiteâ€™s SEO positively.</p>\n<p>But it can have a negative effect on your site. Sometimes those links contain malicious scripts which can make your site vulnerable to hacking.</p>\n<p>Some SEO experts argue that it doesnâ€™t harm your site directly unless you click the links, but it can harm your business growth for sure. Lots of referrer spam can massively distort your analytics report and curb your ability to analyze your siteâ€™s performance.</p>\n<p>Similarly, if you need to show your site statistics to investors or business partners, these spam links can create a bad impression and spoil the deal.</p>\n<p>So, letâ€™s check out how to block WordPress referrer spam in Google Analytics using 3 methods / steps.</p>\n<h3>1. Using a Strong Security Tool/ Software</h3>\n<p>Referrer spam is just one kind of spam that can affect your site; your site can be hit by a wide variety of spam and security attacks. So, you should be always prepared and plug up those security holes.</p>\n<p>To avoid the various different types of security threats to your WordPress site, you can use a powerful security tool like <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/refer/sucuri/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Sucuri</a>.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/refer/sucuri/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-165733\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/sucuri-security-tool.jpg\" alt=\"sucuri-security-tool\" width=\"620\" height=\"311\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/sucuri-security-tool.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/sucuri-security-tool-300x150.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/refer/sucuri/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Sucuri</a> is a powerful security and firewall software for WordPress sites. It protects your site against malware and Trojans as well as referrer spam.</p>\n<p>Sucuri Website Firewall blocks the most well-known spammy referrals by default. And, whenever it detects new referral spammers, it adds them to your block list so they cannot attack your site.</p>\n<h3>2. Blocking Referrer Spam in WordPress Using a Plugin</h3>\n<p>The second method is to install a WordPress plugin that blocks referral spam. If you look into the WordPress plugin repository, you can find plenty of security plugins. However, weâ€™ve chosen theÂ <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/block-referer-spam/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Block Referer Spam</a> plugin for this tutorial.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/block-referer-spam/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-165735\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/block-referrer-spam-plugin.jpg\" alt=\"block-referrer-spam-plugin\" width=\"620\" height=\"201\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/block-referrer-spam-plugin.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/block-referrer-spam-plugin-300x97.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p>First, youâ€™ll need to install and activate the plugin on your WordPress site. After itâ€™s activated, youâ€™ll see aÂ <strong>Referer Spam</strong> menu added in your dashboard menu.</p>\n<p>When you hover your mouse pointer on it, youâ€™ll see 2 submenus: <strong>Referer Spam</strong> and <strong>All Blocked Sites</strong>. If you click onÂ <strong>All Blocked Sites</strong>, youâ€™ll see the list of sites that are already blocked by the plugin.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-165736\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/block-referrer-spam-plugin-optionsjpg.jpg\" alt=\"block-referrer-spam-plugin-options.jpg\" width=\"620\" height=\"416\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/block-referrer-spam-plugin-optionsjpg.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/block-referrer-spam-plugin-optionsjpg-300x201.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, to configure the plugin&#8217;s settings and add custom sites to block, you&#8217;ll need to click on theÂ <strong>Referer Spam</strong> submenu.</p>\n<p>There, you can select <strong>Auto Update</strong> orÂ <strong>Block Mode</strong>. Also, you can force a manual update of the referrer spam list.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-165737\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/blockreferrerspam-auto-autoupdate.jpg\" alt=\"blockreferrerspam-auto-autoupdate\" width=\"620\" height=\"416\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/blockreferrerspam-auto-autoupdate.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/blockreferrerspam-auto-autoupdate-300x201.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>If you see referrer spam links in your Google Analytics report that arenâ€™t listed in the updated list, then youâ€™ll need to add them to the custom block list. All you need to do to add custom block links is copy the links and paste them in the text area next to <strong>Custom Blocks</strong>. Donâ€™t forget to click <strong>Save Changes</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-165738\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/block-referrer-spam-custom-blocks.jpg\" alt=\"block-referrer-spam-custom-blocks\" width=\"620\" height=\"362\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/block-referrer-spam-custom-blocks.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/block-referrer-spam-custom-blocks-300x175.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, the plugin will block those referrer spam links.</p>\n<h3>3. Set Up Google Analytics Filtering to Block Ghost Referrals</h3>\n<p>Even after applying the 2 methods we suggested above, you may still see referrer spam in your Analytics reports sometimes. Itâ€™s because these websites arenâ€™t visiting your site at all. Hence, <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/refer/sucuri/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Sucuri</a> or other plugins cannot block them.</p>\n<p>This referral spam is called ghost spam. They send out requests directly to Google Analytics using your UA Tracking code. This code is used to connect your WordPress site with your Google Analytics account, so itâ€™s often added to the siteâ€™s header section. Because of this, anyone can find out the code and generate referrer spam using it.</p>\n<p>In order to block those websites, you&#8217;ll need to set up filters in Google Analytics.</p>\n<p>First, log into your Google Analytics account and then go to <strong>Audience Â» Technology Â» Network</strong>.</p>\n<p>Then, select <strong>Hostname</strong> as the primary dimension and expand the result to <strong>Monthly</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-165744\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/ga-spammyreferrals.jpg\" alt=\"ga-spammyreferrals\" width=\"520\" height=\"356\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/ga-spammyreferrals.jpg 520w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/ga-spammyreferrals-300x205.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 520px) 100vw, 520px\" /></p>\n<p>There, youâ€™ll see a list of hostnames with many spam hostnames. Now, note down the valid hostnames for your website to create a filter. For example, www.monsterinsights.com and monsterinsights.com, are the valid hostnames for our website.</p>\n<p>Next, you&#8217;ll need to create a filter that includes only the valid hostnames for your site. To do so, click on <strong>Admin</strong> at the end of the left-hand side&#8217;s Analytics panel. Then go to <strong>Filters</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-165752\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/ganalytics-filter-option.jpg\" alt=\"ganalytics-filter-option\" width=\"620\" height=\"555\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/ganalytics-filter-option.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/ganalytics-filter-option-300x269.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Youâ€™ll see the filter screen with anÂ <strong>Add Filter</strong> button. Click the button to get started. Now, you&#8217;ll have to enter your filter information here.</p>\n<p>First, add your filter name (for example, Valid Hostname Filter). Then, select Custom as your filter type and click <strong>Include</strong>. Below that, make sure that <strong>Filter Field</strong> is <strong>Hostname</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-165753\" src=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-filter-ganalytics-settings.jpg\" alt=\"add-filter-ganalytics-settings\" width=\"620\" height=\"555\" srcset=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-filter-ganalytics-settings.jpg 620w, https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/add-filter-ganalytics-settings-300x269.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, you&#8217;ll see <strong>Filter Pattern</strong> box where you have to enter your valid hostnames using Regex string.</p>\n<p>The format is simple, you will need to add a ^ sign before each hostname and a $ sign after it. Use | sign to separate hostnames.</p>\n<p>So, your list of valid hostnames in the Filter Patter will look like below:</p>\n<p>^monsterinsights.com$|^example.monsterinsights.com$</p>\n<p>After that, click the <strong>Save</strong> button. Then, you can check your Google Analytics reports after 24 hours to see the changes.</p>\n<p>We hope this article helped to learn how to block WordPress referrer spam in Google Analytics. You may also want to check out our complete guide on <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/how-to-create-google-analytics-advanced-segments/\">creating advanced segments in Google Analytics</a>.</p>\n<p>And donâ€™t forget to follow us on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/monsterinsights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> for more helpful Google Analytics tips.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/block-wordpress-referrer-spam-in-google-analytics/\">How to Block WordPress Referrer Spam in Google Analytics</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com\">MonsterInsights</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:87:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/block-wordpress-referrer-spam-in-google-analytics/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:3:{s:4:\"href\";s:37:\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/feed/\";s:3:\"rel\";s:4:\"self\";s:4:\"type\";s:19:\"application/rss+xml\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:44:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/\";a:2:{s:12:\"updatePeriod\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"hourly\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:15:\"updateFrequency\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}}}}}}s:4:\"type\";i:128;s:7:\"headers\";O:42:\"Requests_Utility_CaseInsensitiveDictionary\":1:{s:7:\"\0*\0data\";a:10:{s:6:\"server\";s:12:\"nginx/1.15.2\";s:4:\"date\";s:29:\"Mon, 19 Nov 2018 18:18:42 GMT\";s:12:\"content-type\";s:34:\"application/rss+xml; charset=UTF-8\";s:10:\"set-cookie\";s:98:\"srv_id=642bb54d8df0b663ead3557fbe5bd9fa; expires=Mon, 19-Nov-18 19:18:41 GMT; max-age=3600; path=/\";s:13:\"last-modified\";s:29:\"Mon, 19 Nov 2018 17:25:55 GMT\";s:4:\"etag\";s:34:\"\"708e15d4b7ed37c711b9e00825f5f17b\"\";s:12:\"x-robots-tag\";s:15:\"noindex, follow\";s:4:\"link\";s:68:\"<https://www.monsterinsights.com/wp-json/>; rel=\"https://api.w.org/\"\";s:9:\"x-backend\";s:22:\"awesomemotive-web6.com\";s:25:\"strict-transport-security\";s:13:\"max-age=86400\";}}s:5:\"build\";s:14:\"20130911040210\";}', 'no');
